`вҳ… Insight в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ`
**The debounce pattern used here is "leading-edge gated"** вҖ” instead of the typical trailing-edge debounce (fire after quiet period), we gate the *start* of the action behind a timer. The key insight: `diffHoldRef` is set `true` immediately (so the system knows D is being held), but the actual visual strip is delayed 150ms. If keyup arrives before the timer fires, `clearTimeout` cancels it and nothing visual happens. This is cleaner than a leading-edge debounce because it avoids the "undo what just happened" flash entirely.

**Why 150ms?** Human perception of a "tap" vs "hold" is ~100-200ms. 150ms is long enough to filter out taps but short enough that intentional holds feel responsive. Photoshop uses ~120ms for similar peek interactions.
`в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ`

